value.value: A rare, hormonally functioning or non-functioning pituitary gland adenocarcinoma that produces growth hormone. It may be associated with acromegaly.
A controversial term, used for renal papillary lesions which measure 1cm or less in diameter and contain small, regular nuclei.

label.value: type 1 papillary adenoma of the kidney
type 2 papillary adenoma of the kidney

value.value: A genetic deficiency of any of the component of the complement system (including the classical, alternative, and terminal pathway components), that can either be acquired or inherited.
A carcinoma that arises from epithelial cells of the cardia of stomach.
A carcinoma that arises from glandular epithelial cells of the cardia of stomach.

label.value: malignant thyroid stimulating hormone producing neoplasm of pituitary gland

value.value: A rare, hormonally functioning or non-functioning pituitary gland adenocarcinoma that produces thyrotropin.
An adenoma or carcinoma of the anterior lobe of the pituitary gland that produces thyrotropin.

A malignant neoplasm of the ovary with an invasive epithelial component and a fibrotic stroma. The epithelial component is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells with intracytoplasmic mucin. Cystic spaces are also present which contain mucoid material.
A rare benign adipose tissue neoplasm of the epicardium of the heart.
A rare benign adipose tissue neoplasm of the heart usually originating in the epicardial or pericardial fatty tissue.

Benign and malignant astrocytomas that arise from astrocytes in the cerebellum. More than 80% of childhood cerebellar astrocytomas are pilocytic astrocytomas which have a favorable prognosis. The remainder are composed of diffuse or fibrillary subtypes with malignant astrocytomas occurring only rarely in the cerebellum during childhood.
A rare benign adipose tissue neoplasm within the cerebral hemisphere often associated with partial or complete agenesis of the corpus callosum.

A rare benign adipose tissue neoplasm of the central nervous system frequently found in midline locations such as the corpus callosum, the quadrigeminal plate, the hypothalamus, the spinal canal or the cauda equina. Some contain Schwann cells, bone, cartilage or hamartomatous blood vessels.
A rare benign adipose tissue neoplasm of the corpus callosum.

Viral infection of the esophagus. It often occurs in immunocompromised patients and it is caused by cytomegalovirus or herpes simplex virus. Symptoms include pain on swallowing, fever, and retrosternal burning.
A disease that is caused by genetic modifications where those modifications are inherited from a parent's genome.

definition.value: Usage note: this is intended only for diseases with an inherited genetic etiology. Somatic genetic mutations are excluded. Some ontologies use the term 'genetic disease' in the sense of inherited disorders only, we are here careful to distinguish.

value.value: A condition in which the thymus gland is abnomally located; this can be secondary to failure of descent during fetal development, or failure of involution.

A slow-growing malignant bone tumor arising from the remnants of the notochord and occurring in the clivus. It is characterized by a lobulated growth pattern, myxoid stroma formation, and the presence of physaliphorous cells.

A slow-growing malignant bone tumor arising from the remnants of the notochord and occurring in the clivus. It is characterized by a lobulated growth pattern, myxoid stroma formation, the presence of physaliphorous cells and cartilage.
A rare type of teratoma that arises from the ovary and resembles a malformed fetus.
A mature teratoma that arises from the ovary and presents as a large solid mass. It contains multiple cysts that vary in size. Small foci of hemorrhage are also present.
A carcinoma that arises from glandular epithelial cells of the major vestibular gland.
A malignant hemangiopericytoma occurring in the adult population.

definition.value: Editor note: check SFT/hemangiopericytoma/spindle cell tumor

value.value: A solitary fibrous tumor/hemangiopericytoma, grade 3 that arises from the brain and occurs in the adult population.

definition.value: Editor note: check SFT/hemangiopericytoma/spindle cell tumor

value.value: A meningioma that affects the anterior visual pathway.
Meningiomas that affects both optic nerves.
A meningioma that affects the cerebellopontine angle.
An eccrine adenocarcinoma that arises from the sweat glands in the vulva.

label.value: melanotic psammomatous malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumor

value.value: A malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumor characterized by the presence of malignant cells that contain melanin and formation of psammoma bodies.

label.value: malignant melanocytic neoplasm of the peripheral nerve sheath

value.value: A rare variant of malignant peripheral nerve sheath tumor. It is characterized by the presence of malignant cells that contain melanin.

An indolent, mature B-cell neoplasm composed of small, round B-lymphocytes. When the bone marrow and peripheral blood are involved, the term chronic lymphocytic leukemia is used. The term small lymphocytic lymphoma is restricted to cases which do not show leukemic involvement of the bone marrow and peripheral blood.

A form of melanoma occurring most often on the plantar, palmar, subungual, and periungual skin. It presents as a pigmented macular lesion with irregular borders. Morphologically, it consists of atypical spindled and dendritic melanocytes. The epidermis is often hyperplastic and there is pagetoid infiltration of the epidermis by anaplastic cells.
An osteosarcoma arising from the liver.

A diffuse or multifocal proliferation of uniform nevoid polygonal cells in the leptomeninges. Cells may spread into the Virchow-Robin spaces without frank invasion of the brain. Diffuse melanocytosis carries a poor prognosis even in the absence of histologic malignancy. (WHO)
A meningioma that affects the anterior foramen magnum.

An abnormal growth of the cells that comprise the tissues of the brainstem. While the tumor may be histologically benign, it can produce great morbidity due to its location. It presents most commonly in the first two decades of life.
An astrocytoma that arises from the brain stem and occurs during childhood.
A serous cystadenoma of the ovary characterized by the presence of small papillary projections in the inner surface of the cysts.
A benign serous neoplasm characterized by the presence of papillary proliferations on the surface of the ovary.
A serous adenocarcinoma that arises from the ovary and is characterized by the presence of a papillary architectural pattern.

label.value: childhood central nervous system mature teratoma

value.value: A mature teratoma that arises from the central nervous system during childhood.
A carcinoma that arises from epithelial cells of the eyelid.

A uveal melanoma that arises from the choroid. It is the most common primary malignant intraocular tumor. It usually affects Caucasians of northern European descent. It usually remains asymptomatic for a long period. When signs and symptoms occur, they include blurred vision, visual field loss, floaters, and ocular pain. Tumor size is the most important factor that relates to prognosis.
A malignant neoplasm of the ovary characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells resembling endometrial cells in a fibrotic stroma.
An infiltrating adenocarcinoma derived from ceruminous glands in the external auditory canal.
An apocrine adenocarcinoma that arises from the sweat glands in the vulva.

A usually aggressive malignant neoplasm arising from the central nervous system. It is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped fibroblasts and collagenous stroma formation in a herringbone growth pattern.
A benign adipose tissue neoplasm of the rectum.
